Basics of C++
Welcome to the Basics of C++ repository! This repository is designed to help beginners get started with C++ by covering fundamental concepts, providing example codes, and presenting practice questions to solidify understanding.

Table of Contents
- Introduction
- Getting Started
- Topics Covered
- Examples
- Practice Questions
- Contributing
- License
  
Introduction
-> C++ is a powerful, high-performance programming language that is widely used in software development, game development, and competitive programming. This repository aims to introduce you to the basics of C++ and guide you through the foundational concepts you need to become proficient.

Getting Started
-> To get started with the materials in this repository, you'll need a C++ compiler and an IDE or text editor. Here are some recommended tools:

Compiler: GCC, Clang, MSVC
~ IDE: Visual Studio, Code::Blocks, CLion
~ Text Editor: Visual Studio Code, Sublime Text, Atom
~ Ensure you have the necessary tools installed before diving into the examples and exercises.

Topics Covered
This repository covers the following topics:

- Introduction to C++
- Basic Syntax
- Data Types and Variables
- Operators
- Control Structures
- Functions
- Arrays and Strings
- Pointers and References
- Object-Oriented Programming Basics
- Standard Template Library (STL)
Each topic includes a brief explanation, followed by example code and practice questions to test your understanding.

Examples
In the examples directory, you will find various example programs that demonstrate the concepts discussed in each topic. These examples are designed to be simple and easy to understand, helping you to grasp the basics quickly.

Practice Questions
The questions directory contains a set of practice questions for each topic. These questions range from simple to challenging, providing you with the opportunity to test your knowledge and improve your problem-solving skills.

Contributing
We welcome contributions to enhance the content and quality of this repository. If you have suggestions, improvements, or additional examples and questions, feel free to submit a pull request. Please follow the contributing guidelines outlined in the CONTRIBUTING.md file.
